<section xml:id="section-factoring-trinomials-when-a-is-not-one">

    <title>Factoring Trinomials when <m>a\ne1</m></title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-factor-trinomials-when-a-is-not-1" /></li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>In the last section, we learned how to factor <m>ax^2+bx+c</m> when <m>a=1</m>. In this section, we will factor trinomials when <m>a\ne1</m>. The Listing Factor Pairs Method no longer works. We have to resort to Factoring by Grouping Methid and Generic Rectangles Method.</p>

        <figure>
            <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
            <video youtube="KW05tQdgDTk" width="70%"/>
            <video youtube="S5Z_v644Ug0" width="70%"/>
        </figure>
    </introduction>

    <subsection>
        <title>Factoring by Grouping</title>

        <p>We learned the AC Method in the last section. We will simply go through some examples.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-factor-ac-2-5-3">
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>2x^2-5x-3</m> with the AC Method.</p>

                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Step 1: We treat <m>2x^2-5x-3</m> as <m>ax^2+bx+c</m>, and we have <m>a=2, b=-5</m> and <m>c=-3</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 2: The product of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> is <m>ac=(2)(-3)=-6</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 3: List all factor pairs of the product <m>-6</m> until we find a pair whose sum is <m>b</m>'s value, <m>-5</m>. The number <m>-6</m> has four factor pairs: <m>1\text{ and }-6, -1\text{ and }6, 2\text{ and }-3, -3\text{ and }3</m>. Among them, the sum of <m>1</m> and <m>-6</m> is <m>-5</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 4: In <m>2x^2-5x-3</m>, break the second term <m>-5x</m> into <m>x</m> and <m>-6x</m>, and then factor by grouping:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>2x^2-5x-3\amp=2x^2+x-6x-3</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=x(2x+1)-3(2x+1)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=(2x+1)(x-3)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-factor-ac-6-5-6">
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m> with the AC Method.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Step 1: We treat <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m> as <m>ap^2+bpq+cq^2</m>, and we have <m>a=6, b=5</m> and <m>c=-6</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 2: The product of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> is <m>ac=(6)(-6)=-36</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 3: List all factor pairs of the product <m>-36</m> until we find a pair whose sum is <m>b</m>'s value, <m>5</m>.</p>
                            <table xml:id="table-factor-pair-of-negative-thirty-six">
                            <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-36</m></caption>
                            <tabular>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>1\cdot(-36)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-35</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-1)\cdot36</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>35</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>2\cdot(-18)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-16</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-2)\cdot18</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>16</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>3\cdot(-12)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-9</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-3)\cdot12</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>4\cdot(-9)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-5</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-4)\cdot9</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                        </table>
                        <p>We found the pair to be <m>-4</m> and <m>9</m>, whose sum is <m>5</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 4: In <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m>, break the second term <m>5pq</m> into <m>-4pq</m> and <m>9pq</m>, and then factor by grouping:
                            <md>
                                <mrow>6p^2+5pq-6q^2\amp=6p^2-4pq+9pq-6q^2</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=2p(3p-2q)+3q(3p-2q)</mrow>
                                <mrow>\amp=(3p-2q)(2p+3q)</mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>6p^2+pq-6q^2</m> with the AC Method.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>Step 1: We treat <m>6p^2+pq-6q^2</m> as <m>ap^2+bpq+cq^2</m>, and we have <m>a=6, b=1</m> and <m>c=-6</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 2: The product of <m>a</m> and <m>c</m> is <m>ac=(6)(-6)=-36</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 3: List all factor pairs of the product <m>-36</m> until we find a pair whose sum is <m>b</m>'s value, <m>1</m>.</p>
                <table>
                            <caption>Factor Pairs of <m>-36</m></caption>
                            <tabular>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <col halign="center"/>
                                <row bottom="medium">
                                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                                    <cell>Factor Pairs</cell>
                                    <cell>Sum</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>1\cdot(-36)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-35</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-1)\cdot36</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>35</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>2\cdot(-18)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-16</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-2)\cdot18</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>16</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>3\cdot(-12)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-9</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-3)\cdot12</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>9</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>4\cdot(-9)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>-5</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-4)\cdot9</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>6\cdot(-6)</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>(-6)\cdot6</m></cell>
                                    <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                    <cell>n/a</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell><m>9\cdot(-4)</m></cell>
                                    <cell>...</cell>
                                    <cell>...</cell>
                                    <cell>...</cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                            </table>
                <p>We have exhausted all factor pairs of <m>-36</m>, but failed to find a pair whose sum is <m>1</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Step 4: We conclude that <m>6p^2+pq-6q^2</m> is prime.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>Once we can factor a basic trinomial like <m>6x^2+5x-6=(3x-2)(2x+3)</m>, we can factor some variations:<md>
            <mrow>6x^2+5x-6\amp=(3x-2)(2x+3)</mrow>
            <mrow>6x^2+5xy-6y^2\amp=(3x-2y)(2x+3y)</mrow>
            <mrow>6x^2y^2+5xy-6\amp=(3xy-2)(2xy+3)</mrow>
        </md></p>

    </subsection>

