    <subsection>
        <title>Generic Rectangle Method</title>

        <p>We will factor the same problems with generic rectangles.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m> with the Generic Rectangle Method.</p>

                <p>To factor <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m> with generic rectangles, we put the first term <m>2x^2y^2</m> and the third term <m>-3</m> into the top left and bottom right boxes, and we have:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Setting up Generic Rectangles to Factor <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,3) node {$2x^2y^2$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Next, we mark the base and height of the top left rectangle. To make its area <m>2x^2y^2</m>, the only choice we have for its base and height is <m>2xy\cdot xy=2x^2y^2</m>. Now the rectangles look like:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Marking the Top Left Rectangle's Base and Height</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,4.5) node {$2xy$};
                                \draw (0.5,3) node {$xy$};
                                \draw (2,3) node {$2x^2y^2$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Next, our task is to come up with the base and height of the bottom right rectangle. Since the area of the rectangle is <m>-3</m>, the product of its base and height must be <m>-3</m>. There are only two options: <m>1</m> and <m>-3</m>, <m>-1</m> and <m>3</m>. We will try <m>1</m> and <m>-3</m> first:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Trying <m>2xy-3</m> and <m>xy+1</m> as Factors of <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,4.5) node {$2xy$};
                                \draw (4,4.5) node {$-3$};
                                \draw (0.5,3) node {$xy$};
                                \draw (0.5,1) node {$1$};
                                \draw (2,3) node {$2x^2y^2$};
                                \draw (4,3) node {$-3xy$};
                                \draw (2,1) node {$2xy$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>The sum of those rectangles' area is <m>2x^2y^2-3xy+2xy-3=2x^2y^2-xy-3</m>, which is different from <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m>. When the leading coefficient is not <m>1</m>, we cannot give up trying <m>1</m> and <m>-3</m> yet; we must switch their positions in the figure and try again:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Trying <m>2xy+1</m> and <m>xy-3</m> as Factors of <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,4.5) node {$2xy$};
                                \draw (4,4.5) node {$1$};
                                \draw (0.5,3) node {$xy$};
                                \draw (0.5,1) node {$-3$};
                                \draw (2,3) node {$2x^2y^2$};
                                \draw (4,3) node {$xy$};
                                \draw (2,1) node {$-6xy$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-3$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Now, the sum of those generic rectangles is <m>2x^2y^2-5xy-3</m>, matching the given trinomial. Dimensions of those generic rectangles show the solution<me>2x^2y^2-5xy-3=(2xy+1)(xy-3)</me></p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <p>Comparing to Factoring by Grouping, the Generic Rectangle Method could be faster, and it makes more sense with an area model. For complicated problems like the next exercise, Factoring by Grouping would most likely be faster. We recommend students master both methods, and try the Generic Rectangle Method first; if it takes too long, use Factoring by Grouping.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m> with the Generic Rectangle Method.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To factor <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m> with generic rectangles, we put the first term <m>6p^2</m> and the third term <m>-3</m> into the top left and bottom right boxes, and we have:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Setting up Generic Rectangles to Factor <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,3) node {$6p^2$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$-6q^2$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>For the top left rectangle, we have the following choices for its dimensions:<me>p\text{ and }6p, 6p\text{ and }p, 2p\text{ and }3p, 3p\text{ and }2p</me>For the bottom right rectangle, we have the following choices for its dimensions:<me>q\text{ and }6q, -q\text{ and }-6q, 6q\text{ and }q, -6q\text{ and }-q,</me><me>2q\text{ and }3q, -2q\text{ and }-3q, 3q\text{ and }2q, -3q\text{ and }-2q</me>With so many choices, it would take a long time to try each one. If we are lucky, we will find the solution:</p>

                <figure>
                    <caption>Trying <m>3p-2q</m> and <m>2p+3q</m> as Factors of <m>6p^2+5pq-6q^2</m></caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                                \draw (1,0) rectangle (5,4);
                                \draw (1,2) -- (5,2);
                                \draw (3,0) -- (3,4);
                                \draw (2,4.5) node {$3p$};
                                \draw (4,4.5) node {$-2q$};
                                \draw (0.5,3) node {$2p$};
                                \draw (0.5,1) node {$-3q$};
                                \draw (2,3) node {$6p^2$};
                                \draw (4,3) node {$-4pq$};
                                \draw (2,1) node {$9pq$};
                                \draw (4,1) node {$6q^2$};
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                        </latex-image-code>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>Dimensions of those generic rectangles show the solution<me>6p^2+5pq-6q^2=(3p-2q)(2p+3q)</me>For problems with too many choices for rectangles' dimensions, we should factor by grouping instead.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

