    <subsection>
        <title>Factoring Trinomials with Common Factor</title>

        <p>When we factor a polynomial, we should always try to factor out the common factor if possible. Let's look at a few examples.</p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>6x^2y^2-15xy-9</m>.</p>

                <p>Notice that <m>3</m> is a common factor in this trinomial, we will factor it out first:<me>6x^2y^2-15xy-9=3(2x^2y^2-5xy-3)</me>Next, we will factor the trinomial inside the parenthesis. According to the result of <xref ref="example-factor-ac-2-5-3">Example</xref>, we have:<md>
                    <mrow>6x^2y^2-15xy-9\amp=3(2x^2y^2-5xy-3)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=3(2xy+1)(xy-3)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>Factor <m>-6p^6q-5p^5q^2+6p^4q^3</m>.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Notice that <m>-p^4q</m> is a common factor in this trinomial, we will factor it out first:<me>-6p^6q-5p^5q^2+6p^4q^3=-p^4q(6p^2+5pq-6q^2)</me>Next, we will factor the trinomial inside the parenthesis. According to the result of <xref ref="example-factor-ac-6-5-6">Example</xref>, we have:<md>
                    <mrow>-6p^6q-5p^5q^2+6p^4q^3\amp=-p^4q(6p^2+5pq-6q^2)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-p^4q(3p-2q)(2p+3q)</mrow>
                </md></p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </subsection>

